      {
        "id": 2511813,
        "name": "Larry Link",
        "username": "Larry_Link",
        "avatar_template": "/user_avatar/www.wineberserkers.com/larry_link/{size}/1312_2.png",
        "created_at": "2018-10-30T05:40:38.000Z",
        "cooked": "<aside class=\"quote no-group quote-modified\" data-post=\"6\" data-topic=\"146791\">\n<blockquote>\n<aside class=\"quote no-group\" data-post=\"5\" data-topic=\"146791\">\n<blockquote>\n<p>had 08 Butteaux last night. A disappointment in the context of the 10 and 04. A bit dilute and lacking vibrant acidity, though smelled nice and had decent fruit. Not Chablis in character, more generic.</p>\n</blockquote>\n</aside>\n<p>Yeah, it\u2019s odd that the 2008 Raveneau wines are comparatively (and I stress comparatively) weak in the context of what is a great Chablis vintage\u2014in the sense that I would prefer the domaine\u2019s 2009s or 2012s (though it to some extent depends on the climat). I suspect it is because the domaine\u2019s style is dependent on achieving dry extract from mature skins, and there wasn\u2019t much skin maturity in 2008. I\u2019m sure analytically the pH of the 08 Butteaux is lower or at least as low as the 10 or the 04, but the wine has less liveliness and character, I agree.</p>\n<p>The surprising thing about the 2010 vintage in Chablis in general is how much more precocious it is than anyone anticipated. I expected to be drinking 11s and 09s while waiting for 10s, but the 10s are much more open than I would have believed they might be five years ago. In some cases I think there\u2019a a bit of botrytis at play.</p>\n</blockquote>\n</aside>\n<p>The 10\u2019s definitely had some botrytis so you may be right. Tanzer also made this comment about the Raveneau 2010\u2019s, which may help explain why they are drinking well young:</p>\n<p>\u201cIncidentally, Raveneau pointed out that a number of the 2010s finished with close to two grams per liter of residual sugar (a bit higher than the 2009s), as the sugar fermentations were trickier to finish in \u201810. This was also true for a number of white wine producers on the Cote d\u2019'Or.\u201d</p>",
